[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1. [bold]Is cycling safe[bold], particularly in towns and cities[bold]?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]In our report 
[normal]Gearing Up
[normal]?
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]we argued that,
[normal] although cycling is increasing in London, safety 
[normal]remain
[normal]s
[normal] a
[normal] cause for conc
[normal]ern.  D
[normal]espite 
[normal]improvements in the cyclist casu
[normal]al
[normal]ty rate between 2001 and 2006, we identified that the 
[normal]rate across all types of casualty (slight, serious and fatal) 
[normal]worsened between 2007 and 2010.  
[normal]After 2006 there was an 
[normal]increase in the number of 
[normal]cyclist 
[normal]casualties per million cycle journeys in London
[normal] and the
[normal] risk of injury to cyclists increased between 2007 and 2010. Moreover, T
[normal]ransport for London (
[normal]TfL
[normal])
[normal] failed to achieve its
[normal] original
[normal] target to improve cycle safety
[normal] and 
[normal]subsequently 
[normal]lowered its target. 
[normal] Ori
[normal]ginally 
[normal]TfL
[normal] aimed to reduce the number of cyclists killed or seriously injured (KSI) by 50 per cent by 2010 compared to the 1994-98 average, but the actual reduction achieved was 18 per cent. 
[normal]TfL
[normal] now has
[normal] 
[normal]a target to reduce all KSI casualties by 40 per cent
[normal] 
[normal]by 2020 
[normal]compared to the 2005-09 average. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We found cyclist
[normal] casualty 
[normal]rates in London compare
[normal]d
[normal] poorly to
[normal] those in 
[normal]other cities where cycling ha
[normal]d
[normal] 
[normal]also
[normal] 
[normal]increased
[normal]. 
[normal]For example, 
[normal]between
[normal] 2001 and 
[normal]2010
[normal],
[normal] New York recorded a drop of 72 per cent in the rate of cycl
[normal]ist KSIs
[normal] in central Manhattan
[normal] whereas in the same p
[normal]eriod in London the drop was 55 per cent on 
[normal]TfL’s
[normal] road network. This is based on an increase in cycling of 255 per cent in New York and 160 per cent in London. 
[normal]Elsewhere
[normal] higher cycling rates have led to fe
[normal]wer casualties. For example, in Copenhagen, as cycling grew by 50 per cent between 1995 and 2010 the risk of cycle casualties reduced four-fold. Although the Mayor believes the ‘safety in numbers’ effect will improve cycling safety in 
[normal]the capital
[normal], we found
[normal] this is not 
[normal]yet
[normal] evident. 
[normal]We, 
[normal]therefore
[normal],
[normal] concluded that it was
[normal] imperative for the Mayor and 
[normal]TfL
[normal] to make improving the safety of cyclists the top priority in all their cycling programmes.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2. What [bold]can [bold]government do to improve cycling safety?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]In our report 
[normal]Gearing Up?
[normal], 
[normal]we made 
[normal]clear the role central, regional and local government 
[normal]bodies 
[normal]ha
[normal]ve
[normal] to play in improving
[normal] cycling safety
[normal] and encourage more cycling
[normal]. 
[normal] We expressed our support for the Mayor’s aspiration to increase cycling but suggested that
[normal] his 
[normal]target of 5 per cent cycling modal share by 2026 was too low and 
[normal]that the
[normal] upward cycling casualty trends could prevent more Londoners cycling. 
[normal] Indeed the 
[normal]Mayor and 
[normal]TfL’s
[normal] Cycle Safety Action Plan
[normal] (2010) recognises
[normal] 
[normal]that 
[normal]concern about 
[normal]safety 
[normal]is
[normal] both the
[normal] most significant barrier for non-cyclists taking up cycling and stop
[normal]s
[normal] 10 per cent of existing cyclists cycling more.  We
[normal] 
[normal]recommended that the Mayor should establish a new target of 10 per cent cycling modal share by 2026 
[normal]and 
[normal]appoint a Cycling Commissioner
[normal] to champion cycling. 
[normal] We wanted the Cycling Commissioner to 
[normal]publish a biennial London Bicycle Account to inform Londoners 
[normal]of 
[normal]the 
[normal]work 
[normal]taking place 
[normal]to improve cycle safety. 
[normal]We also called for more
[normal] invest
[normal]ment in 
[normal]cycling to shift it away from a transport opt
[normal]ion for the few
[normal],
[normal] to a safe and attractive choice for all Londoners. 
[normal]We 
[normal]recommended that 
[normal]the Mayor a
[normal]nd
[normal] 
[normal]TfL
[normal] should
[normal]:
[normal] 
[normal]allocate at least £145 million to cycling in 2013/14 (the equivalent of 2 per cent of 
[normal]TfL’
[normal]s
[normal] 2012/13 budget); 
[normal]com
[normal]mit a minimum of £100 million 
[normal]to
[normal] funding the
[normal] Better
[normal] Junction
[normal]s
[normal] 
[normal]Review (
[normal]over the period of the review);
[normal] 
[normal]and 
[normal]provide at least £60 million (or 20 per cent of 
[normal]TfL
[normal] cycling budget
[normal])
[normal] to fund the
[normal] Biking Borough Programme so it becomes an Outer London Cycling Fund
[normal].
[normal] 
