[normal]3. [bold]Would it be [bold]desirable and [bold]feasible to segregate cyclists from other road users?[bold]&#xa0;[bold]In our report 
[normal]Gearing Up
[normal]?
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]we concluded 
[normal]eriod of the review), recommendations in four broad areas: 1) ndon 
[normal]al authorities have encouraged the provision of cy
[normal]there could, and should, be more segregated
[normal] cycle space in London. Currently, decisions to give cyclists protected space are often turned down because there is a lack of political will to take space from motorised traffic. 
[normal]We heard from 
[normal]cyclist 
[normal]organisations that cyclists should mix with other traf
[normal]fic where possible, and be separated where necessary. Experts told us that any effort promoted as cycling improvement should give cyclists protected space.  We found the lack of protected space for cyclists on cycle superhighways continued to present risks
[normal]. This echoed the findings from our earlier report 
[normal]Pedal Power
[normal] 
[normal](November 2010) which found that users of the first two cycle superhighways were concerned about their safety. Around 60 per cent of over 1,000 cyclists who responded to our survey said they di
[normal]d 
[normal]not 
[normal]feel safer 
[normal]when 
[normal]using the 
[normal]first two 
[normal]cycle superhighways and two-thirds did not feel the
[normal]se
[normal] superhighways were respected by other road users. We 
[normal]recommended the Mayor and 
[normal]TfL
[normal] provide
[normal] greater consistency in the measures along the 
[normal]cycle 
[normal]superhighways suc
[normal]h as a uniform width, improvements to junctions and 20 mph speed limits on busy sections.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In our re
[normal]port 
[normal]Gearing 
[normal]Up?
[normal],
[normal] we recommended the Mayor and 
[normal]TfL
[normal] commit to introducing fundamental cycle safety improvements to
[normal] the road
[normal] junctions
[normal] 
[normal]in their
[normal] Better Junctions Review. 
[normal]They should 
[normal]prioritise the removal of one-way gyratory systems and examin
[normal]e
[normal] the case for introducing 20 mph speed limits at junctions.  
[normal]We also
[normal] recommended tha
[normal]t the Department for Transport
[normal] introduce legislative changes to traffic 
[normal]regulations to enable 
[normal]TfL
[normal] to use new cycle safety solutions such as cyclist eye-level traffic signals. In addition to
[normal] improving
[normal] infrastructure, we 
[normal]wanted to see
[normal] action
[normal] taken
[normal] to improve the interactions of cyclists with other road users especially HGVs.  We
[normal] expressed support for the 
[normal]G
[normal]overnment and 
[normal]European Union
[normal] introduc
[normal]ing 
[normal]legislation to increase the number of vehicles that are retrofitted with cyclist safety equipment such as side guards, close proximity c
[normal]ameras and visual aids. We 
[normal]also recommended that th
[normal]e
[normal] Mayor and 
[normal]Tf
[normal]L
[normal] work with the London Boroughs 
[normal]to 
[normal]make HGV safety training a condition
[normal] 
[normal]in planning consents and for 
[normal]TfL
[normal] 
[normal]to do more with 
[normal]the Metropolitan Police Service to tackle dangerous road use
[normal]. This
[normal] should include
[normal] more
[normal] enforcement activity along busy cy
[normal]cle routes and at collision hotspots and improv
[normal]ing
[normal] driver
[normal]s’
[normal] awareness through education campaigns.  
[normal]In addition, we called on the
[normal] Department for Transport 
[normal]to 
[normal]examine evidence from leading cycling countries about the costs and benefits of stricter responsib
[normal]ility and penalties against dangerous driving 
[normal]and 
[normal]the
[normal] Mayor and 
[normal]TfL
[normal] 
[normal]to
[normal] develop a plan to roll out cycle training across London
[normal].
